          Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monda=
y.Oil assetsA useful framework for socially responsible investing, one that=
 I get mainly from Cliff Asness, is that the point of it is to=C2=A0raise t=
he cost of capital=C2=A0of bad stuff. If lots of people decide that somethi=
ng is bad and they shouldn=E2=80=99t invest in it, then companies that do t=
he bad thing will have a harder time raising capital and will have to pay m=
ore to attract investors; it will be more expensive to do the bad thing, so=
 there will be less of it. The corollary to this is that, if you raise the =
cost of capital of the bad stuff, the=C2=A0returns=C2=A0to people who=C2=A0=
do=C2=A0invest in the bad stuff will be higher, because that=E2=80=99s just=
 what =E2=80=9Ccost of capital=E2=80=9D means. (A company=E2=80=99s cost of=
 capital is the expected returns of the people who invest in it.) If you in=
vest in socially responsible things, you create higher returns for people w=
ho invest in socially irresponsible things, and you forego those returns fo=
r yourself. Which is fine because you aren=E2=80=99t just in it for the ret=
urns; you want to make the world better, too.This is not the only framework=
! You could have a different framework. You could say =E2=80=9Csocially res=
ponsible things will have higher returns in the long run, because future re=
gulations or social shifts or physical effects of climate change will make =
it impossible to do the socially irresponsible things, so the socially irre=
sponsible companies will go to zero and the socially responsible ones will =
gain market share. Therefore we will invest in socially responsible things =
and expect them to have a higher return than the socially irresponsible one=
s.=E2=80=9D This is a very popular theory, in part for the obvious reason t=
hat it tells people what they want to hear: that they can=C2=A0save the wor=
ld=C2=A0and make above-market returns at the same time.=C2=A0One thing to n=
otice is that=C2=A0both=C2=A0of these stories are essentially behavioral. T=
hey purport to identify inefficiencies in the market, ways to make above-ma=
rket returns from other people=E2=80=99s irrationality or shortsightedness =
or non-economic preferences. The first story says: People have non-economic=
 preferences for social responsibility, which makes socially irresponsible =
stocks cheap, so if I buy socially irresponsible stocks I will get an above=
-market return. The second story says: People are irrationally short-sighte=
d about the long-term risk of socially irresponsible behavior, so if I buy =
socially responsible stocks I will get an above-market long-run return.In s=
ome sense both of these stories can=E2=80=99t really be true,[1] but they b=
oth seem plausible.=C2=A0On the one hand we have decades of experience of p=
eople ignoring externalities and minimizing the effects of climate change, =
etc., which suggests the second story =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cpeople irrati=
onally minimize the long-run costs of social irresponsibility=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0might be true.=C2=A0On the other hand, there are a lot of socia=
l-responsibility and environmental/social/governance investors right now, w=
hich suggests that the field might be a bit crowded and taking the other si=
de of it might be lucrative.Anyway. The mechanism for the first theory is: =
You stop buying oil stocks, the cost of capital of oil companies goes up, t=
hey close down their oil rigs and get into wind farming or whatever. People=
 who still=C2=A0do=C2=A0buy oil stocks get a higher expected=C2=A0return, b=
ut the oil companies can=E2=80=99t stay in that business with their new hig=
her cost of capital so they pivot to a more socially acceptable business. A=
 public company will rationally choose to lower its cost of capital by gett=
ing out of socially irresponsible businesses. Also, the public company will=
 develop=C2=A0non-economic=C2=A0preferences about getting out of socially i=
rresponsible businesses. If it keeps operating oil rigs, it will keep getti=
ng annoying shareholder proposals and disapproving looks from BlackRock Inc=
. and  proxy fights. Better to do what all the investors say they want, rat=
her than what makes the most money.All of this suggests that the expected e=
conomic return on the oil companies=E2=80=99=C2=A0assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0its=
 oil fields and so forth =E2=80=94=C2=A0will be high or, to put it another =
way, that those assets will be cheap relative to their expected cash flows.=
 The cash flows are what they are, but if a public company operates those a=
ssets it will have to pay more for capital and deal with angry socially-res=
ponsible shareholders, so it will divest them cheap and not compete to buy =
more.So here you go:Under intense pressure from investors and activists to =
take more action on climate change, some of the world=E2=80=99s biggest oil=
 and gas companies are putting billions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of assets=
 up for sale.Watching from a distance are people like Brian Gilvary, the he=
ad of Ineos Energy, an arm of the private UK chemicals company. As many ene=
rgy companies try to shift from oil to gas and lower carbon technologies, I=
neos is buying up unwanted fossil fuel assets.=E2=80=9CWe have an appetite =
to acquire,=E2=80=9D says Gilvary, the former chief financial officer at UK=
 energy major BP who joined Ineos in December. In March, the company announ=
ced it would acquire Hess Corporation=E2=80=99s oil and gas assets in Denma=
rk for $150m. =E2=80=A6Despite the intense spotlight on the energy sector, =
there are potential buyers for these assets =E2=80=94 from smaller private =
players such as Ineos, independent operators who are backed by private equi=
ty, opaque energy traders and state oil companies. And while the listed oil=
 majors are announcing net zero plans and a downsizing of their traditional=
 businesses, some state-owned companies and producer economies, such as Sau=
di Arabia, are openly discussing plans to raise production.One thing to say=
 about this is that it=E2=80=99s not obviously a win for the environment:Th=
e activists and government officials behind the campaigns believe they lead=
 to reduced investment and production. But in the short term production cou=
ld shift to private or state-owned companies which face much less scrutiny =
over their activities. Some of those new owners will use that relative obsc=
urity to squeeze as much production as they can out of the oilfields they a=
re acquiring without disclosing the environmental consequences.=E2=80=9CThe=
 quickest way to shrink emissions as a major company is to shed assets so y=
ou can hit climate-related targets,=E2=80=9D said Biraj Borkhataria=C2=A0at=
 RBC Capital Markets. =E2=80=9CBut asset sales do nothing for climate chang=
e, you=E2=80=99re just moving emissions from one hand to another.=E2=80=9DB=
ut the other thing to say about it is that it=E2=80=99s still not obvious t=
hat the first story =E2=80=94=C2=A0that socially responsible investing rais=
es the expected return on socially irresponsible assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0is c=
orrect. It could be true that the oil majors divesting these assets are mak=
ing the right=C2=A0economic=C2=A0choice, and that the people who are buying=
 them are just wrong about their long-term returns:The disposals come amid =
rising speculation about =E2=80=9Cstranded assets=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 huge o=
il and gas reserves that might never be extracted if the world pursues the =
Paris climate goals.If those assets are really stranded =E2=80=94=C2=A0if r=
egulation or social pressures or whatever will make it impossible to get oi=
l out of those oil fields =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you probably shouldn=E2=80=99=
t buy them even at low prices; if you are buying them, it might just be bec=
ause you are cynically short-sighted about the long-term costs of climate c=
hange. But the buyers are taking the other side of that=C2=A0bet:The Danish=
 government has said that it intends to halt oil production by 2050, but Gi=
lvary is undeterred. =E2=80=9CThis deal was attractive to us. We know the f=
iscal regime under which we will be operating,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=9CW=
e know what the endgame looks like.=E2=80=9DCrypto scamsLoosely speaking yo=
u could say that there are three sorts of financial scams.=C2=A0The most co=
mmon scams pretend to be=C2=A0legitimate. A scammer comes to you and says s=
he is raising money to invest in some productive purpose, to fund some prod=
uct or activity that people want. You think =E2=80=9Cah, this company is cu=
ring Covid, if it succeeds that will be lucrative, I will put some money in=
.=E2=80=9D There are lots of scams like this, and some are more convincing =
than others, but speaking very broadly it is easy to sympathize with the vi=
ctims of these scams. They thought they were doing a sensible investing thi=
ng, funding good projects with a high expected return, but they were being =
lied to.Some other scams pretend to be=C2=A0illegitimate, or at least, like=
, tricky or unfair. They pretend to be different scams from the scams they =
actually are. Some people invested with Bernie Madoff because they assumed =
his investment fund was front-running his broker-dealer. It wasn=E2=80=99t,=
 it was just a Ponzi scheme, the joke was on them.=C2=A0But they had though=
t the joke would be on someone else. Or people constantly  fall for =E2=80=
=9Cprime bank=E2=80=9D scams, whose premise is something like =E2=80=9Cthe =
Federal Reserve and the Illuminati pay certain select insiders millions of =
dollars to trade Treasury bonds at night,=E2=80=9D don=E2=80=99t even ask.[=
2]=C2=A0You put your money into a prime bank scheme not because you think y=
ou are making a good investment in a productive activity; you put your mone=
y in because you think someone has offered you a special opportunity to put=
 one over on someone else, to extract money for yourself illegitimately.The=
se scams are quite popular because they offer a sense of specialness; they =
fulfill a need for mystery and conspiracies. Also because =E2=80=9Cyou can=
=E2=80=99t cheat an honest man=E2=80=9D: If you are running a scam, the ide=
al mark is someone who is up for a little dishonesty, who is not going to i=
nsist on all the proper procedures. Also because the victims here are never=
 going to be that sympathetic: They wanted to do some scam (one where they =
were the scammer), you served them a different scam (one where they were th=
e victim), but what are they gonna do, call the police?The third kind of sc=
am =E2=80=94=C2=A0is it even a scam? =E2=80=94=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t pretend=
 to be anything at all; it is just open about being exactly the sort of=C2=
=A0scam that it actually is. In  the early days of Ethereum there were tons=
 of things named like =E2=80=9CEthereum Pyramid Scheme=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=
=9CEthereum Ponzi Scheme.=E2=80=9D If you buy that you know what you=E2=80=
=99re getting! The value proposition of a Ponzi scheme is: =E2=80=9CIf you =
put in money now, and other people put in money later, we will pay you a hi=
gh return on your investment, but=C2=A0if you are the last one in you will =
lose all your money.=E2=80=9D You can dress that proposition up in lies =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re investing in totally safe bonds at a=
 guaranteed above-market return=E2=80=9D while actually doing a Ponzi =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0or you could not. You could just tell people what you=E2=80=99r=
e doing and ask them if they want to play. Some will, because that basic Po=
nzi proposition is sort of a fun game of musical chairs but with money. Peo=
ple could want to play because they like a gamble, or because they think th=
ey have some edge =E2=80=94=C2=A0some special psychological insight or insi=
de knowledge or whatever that gives them an advantage in guessing when the =
game will end and getting out in time.I have mostly  come around to  the vi=
ew that many small-cap pump-and-dump schemes look like the first type of sc=
am but are really the third. Some stock shill sends out an email newsletter=
 saying =E2=80=9Cbuy Amalgamated Widgets because they are about to announce=
 a breakthrough Covid cure,=E2=80=9D and then Amalgamated Widgets stock goe=
s up rapidly and then down rapidly again, and from the outside you can look=
 at it and say =E2=80=9Cah, people were tricked into thinking that Amalgama=
ted Widgets had a Covid cure,=E2=80=9D but the shill=E2=80=99s newsletter i=
s titled Stock Shill Weekly and the only subscribers are people who want to=
 play pump-and-dumps and nobody believes it, it=E2=80=99s just an excuse fo=
r everyone to play a gambling game where the loser is whoever gets out last=
.=C2=A0There is no reason at all to sympathize with victims of the third so=
rt of scam; often they don=E2=80=99t sympathize with themselves. They don=
=E2=80=99t perceive themselves as victims, because they aren=E2=80=99t; the=
y think they played a game of chance and lost. They got their money=E2=80=
=99s worth, in expectation; they had their fun and it cost them a reasonabl=
e amount of their gambling money.Obviously in practice these things can blu=
r into each other; if you are playing the fun gambling game (type 3) you mi=
ght also be hoping to get an edge (type 2) from other people believing that=
 the pump is real (type 1).Anyway nobody has ever deserved to get their mon=
ey stolen more than the people in this Bloomberg article titled =E2=80=9CCr=
ypto Scammers Rip Off Billions as Pump-and-Dump Schemes Go Digital=E2=80=9D=
:=E2=80=99Ben Ghrist knows all about crypto scams. He=E2=80=99s lives at hi=
s parents=E2=80=99 home in Roanoke, Texas, and, for the moment, is trading =
meme coins as a full-time job. At 35, Ghrist is a millionaire in Safemoon, =
a billionaire in Kishu Inu and Sanshu Inu and a trillionaire in Keanu Inu. =
He=E2=80=99s got money in at least 15 different coins, with about a quarter=
 of his $25,000 =E2=80=9Cportfolio=E2=80=9D in Dogecoin, the one created as=
 a joke back in 2013 and known for its Shiba Inu mascot.=C2=A0Ghrist suspec=
ts he=E2=80=99s gotten rug-pulled, soft-rugged and even fallen victim to a =
honey pot =E2=80=94 when a seemingly legitimate coin sets up a trap, like t=
he inability for investors to sell once they=E2=80=99ve bought in. Ghrist s=
ays he wanted to trade the momentary 1000% gain of a coin launch called Spa=
ce Jupiter but couldn=E2=80=99t sell for about 20 minutes. He says the crea=
tors of the coin eventually re-enabled selling, but only after the coin pri=
ce had slumped and after he suspects they had taken gains for themselves.=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s pretty much hit-or-miss wherever you go,=E2=80=
=9D says Ghrist, who typically works from his bed with two laptops. He says=
 he=E2=80=99s pulled all-nighters and worked 48 hours straight moiling for =
meme-coin gold.In picking his meme coins, he considers a range of factors t=
o minimize risk. One is the number of social media accounts a coin has (leg=
it coins, he says, tend to have more than dodgy ones). Another is whether t=
hose accounts are public or private (he says public is safer than private):=
 how much time those accounts spend chatting with investors (more is better=
 than less). Then he looks at what=E2=80=99s happening in Telegram groups, =
known in meme-coin-speak as =E2=80=9Cshilling groups.=E2=80=9D When the who=
le package looks slapdash, that=E2=80=99s a bad sign, he says.Ghrist feels =
scammed at times, but he=E2=80=99s pressing on too. =E2=80=9CWhen I feel th=
at fear of losing my money, because I know I might, I also balance that wit=
h I might make five times my money or three times my money,=E2=80=9D he say=
s. =E2=80=9CYou can literally do 30 times or more if you if you get a coin =
that lasts more than a day.=E2=80=9DNobody in this article thinks that they=
 are investing in some productive enterprise and hoping to earn an attracti=
ve rate of return. Nobody thinks that Keanu Inu is the future of money and =
that they are contributing to innovation in payments systems. They all thin=
k they can =E2=80=9Cdo 30 times or more=E2=80=9D on some completely pointle=
ss gambling game, and if they lose, well, =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s pretty much=
 hit-or-miss wherever you go.=E2=80=9D Let them take each other=E2=80=99s m=
oney, who cares.


