<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><h2 style=3D"font-weight=
: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;=
 letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px 5px;">Oil assets</h2><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A useful framework for socially responsible inves=
ting, one that I get mainly <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/24393206.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXFyLmNvbS9JbnNpZ2h0cy9QZXJzcGVjd=
Gl2ZXMvVmlydHVlLWlzLWl0cy1Pd24tUmV3YXJkLU9yLU9uZS1NYW5zLUNlaWxpbmctaXMtQW5v=
dGhlci1NYW5zLUZsb29y/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBee82176f" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">from Cliff Asness</a>, is tha=
t the point of it is to=C2=A0<em>raise the cost of capital=C2=A0</em>of bad=
 stuff. If lots of people decide that something is bad and they shouldn=E2=
=80=99t invest in it, then companies that do the bad thing will have a hard=
er time raising capital and will have to pay more to attract investors; it =
will be more expensive to do the bad thing, so there will be less of it. Th=
e corollary to this is that, if you raise the cost of capital of the bad st=
uff, the=C2=A0<em>returns=C2=A0</em>to people who=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>inv=
est in the bad stuff will be higher, because that=E2=80=99s just what =E2=
=80=9Ccost of capital=E2=80=9D means. (A company=E2=80=99s cost of capital =
is the expected returns of the people who invest in it.) If you invest in s=
ocially responsible things, you create higher returns for people who invest=
 in socially irresponsible things, and you forego those returns for yoursel=
f. Which is fine because you aren=E2=80=99t just in it for the returns; you=
 want to make the world better, too.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This i=
s not the only framework! You could have a different framework. You could s=
ay =E2=80=9Csocially responsible things will have higher returns in the lon=
g run, because future regulations or social shifts or physical effects of c=
limate change will make it impossible to do the socially irresponsible thin=
gs, so the socially irresponsible companies will go to zero and the sociall=
y responsible ones will gain market share. Therefore we will invest in soci=
ally responsible things and expect them to have a higher return than the so=
cially irresponsible ones.=E2=80=9D This is a very popular theory, in part =
for the obvious reason that it tells people what they want to hear: that th=
ey can=C2=A0save the world=C2=A0and make above-market returns at the same t=
ime.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing to notice is that=C2=
=A0both<em>=C2=A0</em>of these stories are essentially behavioral. They pur=
port to identify inefficiencies in the market, ways to make above-market re=
turns from other people=E2=80=99s irrationality or shortsightedness or non-=
economic preferences. The first story says: People have non-economic prefer=
ences for social responsibility, which makes socially irresponsible stocks =
cheap, so if I buy socially irresponsible stocks I will get an above-market=
 return. The second story says: People are irrationally short-sighted about=
 the long-term risk of socially irresponsible behavior, so if I buy sociall=
y responsible stocks I will get an above-market long-run return.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some sense both of these stories can=E2=80=99t rea=
lly be true,[1] but they both seem plausible.=C2=A0On the one hand we have =
decades of experience of people ignoring externalities and minimizing the e=
ffects of climate change, etc., which suggests the second story =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cpeople irrationally minimize the long-run costs of social ir=
responsibility=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0might be true.=C2=A0On the other han=
d, there are a lot of social-responsibility and environmental/social/govern=
ance investors right now, which suggests that the field might be a bit crow=
ded and taking the other side of it might be lucrative.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Anyway. The mechanism for the first theory is: You stop buying=
 oil stocks, the cost of capital of oil companies goes up, they close down =
their oil rigs and get into wind farming or whatever. People who still=C2=
=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>buy oil stocks get a higher expected=C2=A0return, but t=
he oil companies can=E2=80=99t stay in that business with their new higher =
cost of capital so they pivot to a more socially acceptable business. A pub=
lic company will rationally choose to lower its cost of capital by getting =
out of socially irresponsible businesses. Also, the public company will dev=
elop=C2=A0<em>non-economic=C2=A0</em>preferences about getting out of socia=
lly irresponsible businesses. If it keeps operating oil rigs, it will keep =
getting annoying shareholder proposals and disapproving looks from BlackRoc=
k Inc. and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2439320=
6.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMD=
UtMjcvZXh4b24tbG9zdC1hLWNsaW1hdGUtcHJveHktZmlnaHQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
19c76af2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 proxy fights</a>. Better to do what all the investors say they want, rathe=
r than what makes the most money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of th=
is suggests that the expected economic return on the oil companies=E2=80=99=
=C2=A0<em>assets </em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0its oil fields and so forth =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0will be high or, to put it another way, that those assets will be che=
ap relative to their expected cash flows. The cash flows are what they are,=
 but if a public company operates those assets it will have to pay more for=
 capital and deal with angry socially-responsible shareholders, so it will =
divest them cheap and not compete to buy more.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">So <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24393206.25=
5798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNGRlZTcwODAtM2ExYi00NzlmLWE1MGMtYz=
M2NDFjODJjMTQy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe7eb9f6b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">here you go</a>:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Under intense pressure from investors and activis=
ts to take more action on climate change, some of the world=E2=80=99s bigge=
st oil and gas companies are putting billions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of =
assets up for sale.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Watching from a distanc=
e are people like Brian Gilvary, the head of Ineos Energy, an arm of the pr=
ivate UK chemicals company. As many energy companies try to shift from oil =
to gas and lower carbon technologies, Ineos is buying up unwanted fossil fu=
el assets.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe have an appetite to =
acquire,=E2=80=9D says Gilvary, the former chief financial officer at UK en=
ergy major BP who joined Ineos in December. In March, the company announced=
 it would acquire Hess Corporation=E2=80=99s oil and gas assets in Denmark =
for $150m. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Despite the intense sp=
otlight on the energy sector, there are potential buyers for these assets =
=E2=80=94 from smaller private players such as Ineos, independent operators=
 who are backed by private equity, opaque energy traders and state oil comp=
anies. And while the listed oil majors are announcing net zero plans and a =
downsizing of their traditional businesses, some state-owned companies and =
producer economies, such as Saudi Arabia, are openly discussing plans to ra=
ise production.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing to s=
ay about this is that it=E2=80=99s not obviously a win for the environment:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The activists and government o=
fficials behind the campaigns believe they lead to reduced investment and p=
roduction. But in the short term production could shift to private or state=
-owned companies which face much less scrutiny over their activities. Some =
of those new owners will use that relative obscurity to squeeze as much pro=
duction as they can out of the oilfields they are acquiring without disclos=
ing the environmental consequences.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=
=9CThe quickest way to shrink emissions as a major company is to shed asset=
s so you can hit climate-related targets,=E2=80=9D said Biraj Borkhataria=
=C2=A0at RBC Capital Markets. =E2=80=9CBut asset sales do nothing for clima=
te change, you=E2=80=99re just moving emissions from one hand to another.=
=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the other thing =
to say about it is that it=E2=80=99s still not obvious that the first story=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0that socially responsible investing raises the expected ret=
urn on socially irresponsible assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0is correct. It could be=
 true that the oil majors divesting these assets are making the right=C2=A0=
<em>economic=C2=A0</em>choice, and that the people who are buying them are =
just wrong about their long-term returns:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">The disposals come amid rising speculation about =E2=80=9Cstrand=
ed assets=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 huge oil and gas reserves that might never be =
extracted if the world pursues the Paris climate goals.</p></blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If those assets are really stranded =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0if regulation or social pressures or whatever will make it impossible to=
 get oil out of those oil fields =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you probably shouldn=
=E2=80=99t buy them even at low prices; if you are buying them, it might ju=
st be because you are cynically short-sighted about the long-term costs of =
climate change. But the buyers are taking the other side of that=C2=A0bet:<=
/p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Danish government has said =
that it intends to halt oil production by 2050, but Gilvary is undeterred. =
=E2=80=9CThis deal was attractive to us. We know the fiscal regime under wh=
ich we will be operating,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=9CWe know what the endga=
me looks like.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; fon=
t-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spa=
cing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style:=
 dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px 5px;">Crypto scams</h2><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Loosely speaking you could say that there are three sorts =
of financial scams.=C2=A0The most common scams pretend to be=C2=A0<em>legit=
imate</em>. A scammer comes to you and says she is raising money to invest =
in some productive purpose, to fund some product or activity that people wa=
nt. You think =E2=80=9Cah, this company is curing Covid, if it succeeds tha=
t will be lucrative, I will put some money in.=E2=80=9D There are lots of s=
cams like this, and some are more convincing than others, but speaking very=
 broadly it is easy to sympathize with the victims of these scams. They tho=
ught they were doing a sensible investing thing, funding good projects with=
 a high expected return, but they were being lied to.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Some other scams pretend to be=C2=A0<em>illegitimate</em>, or at=
 least, like, tricky or unfair. They pretend to be different scams from the=
 scams they actually are. Some people invested with Bernie Madoff because t=
hey assumed his investment fund was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/24393206.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvb=
S8yMDA4LzEyL3RoZS1zZWMtbG9va2VkLWludG8tbWFkb2ZmLWZyb250LXJ1bm5pbmctY2xhaW1z=
LWxhc3QteWVhcg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd1707d90" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">front-running his broker-dealer</a>=
. It wasn=E2=80=99t, it was just a Ponzi scheme, the joke was on them.=C2=
=A0But they had thought the joke would be on someone else. Or people consta=
ntly <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24393206.2557=
98/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDktMDMv=
YWNjdXNlZC1mcmF1ZHN0ZXItc3BlbnQtaGlzLW1vbmV5LW9uLW90aGVyLWZyYXVkcw/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB5250e4b8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> fall for =E2=80=9Cprime bank=E2=80=9D scams</a>, whose pr=
emise is something like =E2=80=9Cthe Federal Reserve and the Illuminati pay=
 certain select insiders millions of dollars to trade Treasury bonds at nig=
ht,=E2=80=9D don=E2=80=99t even ask.[2]=C2=A0You put your money into a prim=
e bank scheme not because you think you are making a good investment in a p=
roductive activity; you put your money in because you think someone has off=
ered you a special opportunity to put one over on someone else, to extract =
money for yourself illegitimately.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These sc=
ams are quite popular because they <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/24393206.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW=
