<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">PFOF</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robinhood Markets Inc. filed fo=
r an initial public offering last week, which I suppose means it=E2=80=99s =
time to talk about payment for order flow again. Here is a <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24393206.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3=
NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9yb2Jpbmhvb2RzLWRlYnV0LWlzLWNsb3VkZWQtYnktc2VjLXNjcnV0a=
W55LW9mLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZsb3ctMTE2MjU2NTU2MDA_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9z=
Mw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa3727528" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: soli=
d; background-color: #ccc;">Wall Street Journal article</a>:</p><blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robinhood Markets Inc. is on a collision cour=
se with regulators over a controversial practice that generates most of its=
 revenue, as the online brokerage gears up for a highly anticipated initial=
 public offering.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In its IPO filing, releas=
ed Thursday, Robinhood disclosed that 81% of its first-quarter revenue came=
 from sending its customers=E2=80=99 stock, options and cryptocurrency orde=
rs to high-speed trading firms=E2=80=94a practice known as payment for orde=
r flow.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Payment for order flow, or PFOF, ma=
kes it possible for Robinhood to let customers place trades with no upfront=
 commission payment. Zero-commission stock trades helped the company win ov=
er millions of younger, less affluent customers and are now standard practi=
ce at many of Robinhood=E2=80=99s competitors.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Payment for order flow critics=E2=80=94including the country=E2=80=99s =
top market regulator, Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman Gary Gens=
ler =E2=80=94are wary of the practice. They argue that it poses a conflict =
of interest for brokerages, because the brokers can either collect more mon=
ey for selling their customers=E2=80=99 order flow or pass that money on to=
 customers in the form of price savings on their trades. Last month, Mr. Ge=
nsler said the SEC was reviewing payment for order flow, fueling speculatio=
n among some market observers that PFOF could be banned.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe entire business model of some brokers is in the =
crosshairs,=E2=80=9D said Tyler Gellasch, executive director of Healthy Mar=
kets Association, an investor trade group. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Still, the SEC hasn=E2=80=99t given any indication of how it migh=
t change its rules on payment for order flow. Prohibiting PFOF might force =
some brokerages to abandon zero-commission trading, which could lead to an =
outcry as small investors face the prospect of paying for trades again. Tha=
t would undermine arguments that banning PFOF would help investors. Many of=
 the potential benefits of such a change=E2=80=94such as possibly increased=
 activity on transparent public exchanges=E2=80=94wouldn=E2=80=99t be as ta=
ngible to ordinary investors.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
The problem with payment-for-order-flow discourse is that it is mostly abou=
t best execution. Robinhood gets a customer order to buy or sell a stock an=
d sends it to a market maker (a wholesaler, internalizer, electronic tradin=
g firm). The market maker fills the order (selling stock to a customer who =
wants to buy, buying stock from a customer who wants to sell) and=C2=A0pays=
 Robinhood a little bit of money for each order that it sees. The market ma=
ker makes money. This infuriates people. They think: If the market maker is=
 making money filling these orders, and if it is paying Robinhood for the r=
ight to fill these orders, then it must be filling those orders at a=C2=A0<=
em>bad price</em>. If Robinhood routes your order to a market maker who pay=
s for order flow, you must be getting a worse price than you would if Robin=
hood routed your order to the stock exchange and just took the best price a=
vailable there.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is a reasonable intuit=
ion but it is wrong! It is wrong! You actually generally get filled at a=C2=
=A0<em>better=C2=A0</em>price than you=E2=80=99d get on the stock exchange!=
 I keep saying this,=C2=A0and I explain why in detail, and then each time l=
ike a dozen people email me to be like =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=99re so naive, if=
 the market maker is paying for the order then how can I be getting a bette=
r price?=E2=80=9D So I do not harbor any hope of changing anyone=E2=80=99s =
mind on this point. You can read <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/24393206.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDUvcm9iaW5ob29kLWdhbWVzdG9wLXNhZ2EtcHJlc3N1cmVzLXB=
heW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZsb3c/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB31859452" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a fuller intuitive ex=
planation here</a>, or not, but either way please please please do not emai=
l me to say =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=99re so naive, if the market maker is paying=
 for the order then how can I be getting a better price?=E2=80=9D</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Please also do not email me to say more sophisticate=
d things like =E2=80=9Cif market makers were not able to segregate retail o=
rders then lit spreads would be tighter and everyone, even retail, would be=
 getting better fills.=E2=80=9D That one may be true; it=E2=80=99s just not=
 what I want to talk about right now. Or there is Gensler=E2=80=99s point t=
hat=C2=A0you could offer more price improvement instead of taking payment f=
or order flow; that is true (and Robinhood has <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24393206.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMDcvdGhlLWlwby1tYXJrZXQtd2FzLXRvby1nb=
29k/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7bbb66b1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: sol=
id; background-color: #ccc;"> gotten in trouble for it</a>), but not what I=
 want to discuss here.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead I want=
 to talk about the=C2=A0<em>actual=C2=A0</em>conflict of interest in Robinh=
ood=E2=80=99s use of payment for order flow, which is not not not not not n=
ot not not not not not not not about execution quality. The conflict is not=
 not not not not not not =E2=80=9Cif market makers pay Robinhood for orders=
, it will route those orders to the market maker who pays the most, not the=
 one who will give its customers the best price.=E2=80=9D[3] For one thing,=
 Robinhood customers do generally get a better price than is available on t=
he stock exchange. For another thing, though, we are talking about, often,=
=C2=A0fractions of pennies per share. If you bought GameStop Corp. stock wh=
en it was trading at $483, I simply do not care if you paid $483.01 or $483=
.007 or even $483.20, and neither should you.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">The actually important conflict is: =E2=80=9CIf market makers pay Robinh=
ood for orders, it will try to generate a lot of orders, particularly ones =
that pay the most.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What that means=
 is that,=C2=A0if Robinhood gets paid primarily for order flow, it has ince=
ntives to encourage a lot of trading, and in particular a lot of trading of=
 options, because it gets paid more for options orders than for most stock =
orders. And so in fact Robinhood customers trade a lot,[4] and in particula=
r they trade a lot of=C2=A0options, and Robinhood makes a ton of money from=
 their options trading.=C2=A0I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/24393206.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMDIvcm9iaW5ob29kLWlwby1maWxpbmctaXMtYS1sZXNzb24taW4tb=
WVtZS1maW5hbmNl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB546338fc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">said last week</a> that =E2=80=9CE=
conomically, Robinhood is an options brokerage. Robinhood=E2=80=99s main bu=
siness is convincing people to trade options, and then having options marke=
t makers pay to take the other side of those trades,=E2=80=9D and more than=
 a third of its revenue comes from options trades. Retail options trades ar=
e lucrative for market makers, so they pay Robinhood a lot for them.=C2=A0<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course any commission-based broker also =
has an incentive to encourage trading, and there are lots of enforcement ca=
ses against brokers who get their customers to trade too much. (This is usu=
ally called =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/24393206.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9vaWVhL2ludmVzdG9yLWFsZXJ0cy1i=
dWxsZXRpbnMvaWFfZXhjZXNzaXZldHJhZGluZy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbb9fe=
793" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">churn=
ing</a>.=E2=80=9D) But there is a natural limit on a commission-based broke=
r=E2=80=99s ability to churn, which is that if you are a customer and you p=
ay $5 per trade, you will wince every time you pay that $5, and eventually =
you will stop. At zero-commission brokerages =E2=80=94=C2=A0like Robinhood,=
 which pioneered the model =E2=80=94=C2=A0you pay $0 per trade, you never w=
ince, and you never stop.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you could have=
 a reasonable theory of Robinhood that says that all of its alleged problem=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/24393206.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLnN0YXRlLm1hLnVzL3NjdC9jdXJyZW5=
0L3NjdHJvYmluaG9vZC9yb2Jpbmhvb2RpZHguaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9c2800bd=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">gamifica=
tion</a>,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0the psychological tactics it uses to get people to =
keep coming back to the app and trading more, as well as its <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24393206.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMDEvcHVtcC1hbmQtZHVtcC1=
hbmQtcHVsbC10aGUtcnVn/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB284d5871" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">somewhat lax restrictions</a=
> on who is allowed to trade options =E2=80=94=C2=A0are symptoms of one und=
erlying business-model decision, which is to make almost all of its money f=
rom payment for order flow. If you make money mainly from net interest marg=
in, you will want to accumulate customer cash and margin balances. If you m=
ake money from investment products that you manage, you will push those pro=
ducts. If you make money from commissions, you will push people to trade a =
lot, but it will work imperfectly. If you make money from payment for order=
 flow, you will push people to trade a lot, and it will work really well.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If trading a lot is bad for people, this is =
bad. It is perhaps not=C2=A0<em>obvious=C2=A0</em>that trading a lot is bad=
 for people, but it does seem intuitive. =E2=80=9CThe majority of our custo=
mers prefer to buy and hold,=E2=80=9D say Robinhood=E2=80=99s founders in t=
heir introduction to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/24393206.255798/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE3=
ODM4NzkvMDAwMTYyODI4MDIxMDEzMzE4L3JvYmluaG9vZHMtMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
